Here's the proper approach using MAUI's app lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. In your `NotePage.xaml.cs`, save/restore via lifecycle events:**

```csharp
public partial class NotePage : ContentPage
{
    private const string DraftKey = "NoteDraft";

    public NotePage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
    }

    protected override void OnAppearing()
    {
        base.OnAppearing();

        // Restore draft
        if (Preferences.ContainsKey(DraftKey))
            NoteEditor.Text = Preferences.Get(DraftKey, string.Empty);

        // Subscribe to lifecycle events
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated += OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated += OnAppResumed;
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        App.Current.Windows[0].Deactivated -= OnAppBackgrounded;
        App.Current.Windows[0].Activated -= OnAppResumed;
    }

    private void OnAppBackgrounded(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Save draft when app goes to background
        Preferences.Set(DraftKey, NoteEditor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void OnAppResumed(object sender, EventArgs e)
    {
        // Optional: confirm restore or refresh UI
    }

    public void ClearDraft()
    {
        // Call this after the user explicitly saves/discards
        Preferences.Remove(DraftKey);
    }
}
```

**2. Your `NotePage.xaml`:**

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             x:Class="YourApp.NotePage">
    <VerticalStackLayout Padding="16">
        <Editor x:Name="NoteEditor"
                Placeholder="Write your note..."
                HeightRequest="300" />
        <Button Text="Save Note" Clicked="OnSaveClicked" />
    </VerticalStackLayout>
</ContentPage>
```

**Key points:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| **Where to save** | `Preferences` — lightweight key-value store, perfect for small text |
| **When to save** | `Window.Deactivated` fires when the app backgrounds |
| **When to restore** | `OnAppearing` + `Window.Activated` |
| **Cleanup** | Call `ClearDraft()` after the user intentionally saves or discards |

> **Tip:** If drafts could be large, use `SecureStorage` or write to `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory` instead of `Preferences`, which is designed for small values.
